<title>UK: GEC to benefit from Labour tax plans - Lehman.</title>
<headline>GEC to benefit from Labour tax plans - Lehman.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-06-11</dateline>
<text>
<p>General Electric Co Plc, the FTSE 100's second-to-top gainer on Wednesday, was highlighted in a Lehman Brothers research note as a potential beneficiary of new Labour's upcoming budget.</p>
<p>GEC rose 7-1/2p to 361p, or 2.1 percent, second only to bid target Energy Group Plc which jumped 11 percent.</p>
<p>Companies with high capital expenditure or high levels of R&amp;D spending look best placed to benefit from changes to corporate tax in the budget, the note said.</p>
<p>GEC, British Aerospace Plc, and Rolls-Royce Plc are the top three R&amp;D spenders as a percentage of market capitalisation in the FTSE 100, the note said.</p>
<p>Lehman added GEC to its &quot;Recommended Portfolio&quot; rating from &quot;2-Outperform&quot;.</p>
<p>Imperial Chemical Industries Plc, Burton Group Plc and Tate and Lyle Plc are the top three in the FTSE 100 in terms of purchases of fixed assets as a percentage of market capitalisation, Lehman said.</p>
<p>-- Louise Ireland, London Newsroom +44 171 542 7717</p>
